description.text: You jailbroke your iPhone, now let your iPhone break YOU out of jail! This rugged case has a rear compartment to hold a lock picking set to help you get out of sticky situations with the law.

• Print case.

  • either print lockpicks or use your own.

  • Put picks in compartment.

  • Insert phone.

  • Rest easy in the fact that no door can hold you back from freedom!
    • Note: This is for satire. Don't use this to break out of jail. We all know the prison guards will confiscate your phone from you. ;)

description.text: EDIT: New updated version adds the ability to specify 3D variants of the flake, similar to Fugmulch's 3D snowflake ornament (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:190744). Render the full version in customizer and it will generate multiple STLs, one for each flake and one for a connector that keeps it in place. Flat packable - great for putting inside cards! One of my fondest memories as a child was making cut paper ornaments at the holidays - folding up paper, making little cuts in the wedge of paper, and then unfolding to see my creation. Now you can do the same online and 3D print them! Using customizer, you can either draw online or upload a picture from a drawing. Great fun for making ornaments with kids (and showing them the basics of 3D printing!) More features to come... notably multi-dimension flakes!

This side guard was designed to prevent air flow from the fan to move sideways and flow over the print area. This cold air flow can make the print cool down and warp.
Installation is very simple.
Video can be found here:
https://youtu.be/-qFXvTFALUY
There are two versions. Choose and print the version you need.
Also, when placing the STL in the slicer, rotate the part so that it stays like the picture attached.

title: Support horizontal / stand horizontal  :   UE Boom 2

description.text:
Support pour UE Boom 2

Deux version :

  • Pieds non joignable : conseillé pour fixation des pieds sur autre support
    socle droit + socle gauche a imprimer

  • Pieds joignable : conseillé pour pied transportable et a poser
    support gauche avec trou + support droit avec trou + 100mm separation + colle

Two model :

  • foot independent, recommended for fix on another support ( desk, wall ...)
    printed : socle droit + socle gauche

  • foots linked recommended for transportable, or just pose
    printed socle droit avec trou + socle gauche avec trou + glue

I have my filament reel at the 10:30 position beding my printer. I added a 2nd dgide on the filament arm. I think there is room for more optimisation, filament still drags on the forner of the frame, and also on the edge of the guide loop when x=0.

The top part could be printed as a single piece, but this is just how i ended up building it.

Be aware that using this does add some drag to the filament, which I'm not really happy with. There is scope for polishing the loop a little more, but I've started by upping my extruder feed rate to 105%.

I subsequently tried using a printed roller and bearing, but actually that ended up worse, and I've reverted to using this part now.

print_settings.Notes:: These pieces are very thin so I printed with 100% infill to avoid cracking.

description.text:
I love taking magnets out of things, and one thing I hate is throwing perfectly good magnets away. Secondly, I hate weak fridge magnets. Thirdly, I hate magnets that come off because the glue fails.   
Print and insert a Sonicare magnet into this thing to create a cool fridge magnet. I only designed a single top, but the included files can be used so you can attach a different topper of your own design.

Use a pair of pliers or screw driver, (pro tip: use caution, and something to protect the magnet's surface if using pliers like a thin piece of cardboard), to remove the magnet from a Sonicare toothbrush head.  
Pause right before top layer starts, and insert magnet, then resume.

description.text:
When the mouse turns the fence to get to the bait, the fence falls in a groove and locks in place.
Not tested, my Makerbot is out-of-order for now.
Have fun!

Print the box, the fence and the top. 
Print some feet if you don't have anything to make a space between the box and the ground. 
Place a bait where the star is.
Carefully place the fence so that when the mouse is almost at the bait, it falls and locks in place. 
There should be plenty of space between the interlocking pieces, so don't worry if your printer isn't fine tuned. (But it also means you might want to tape the top on the box, just to be sure.)

description.text:
Yet Another Lack Table Enclosure. Inspired by the many great designs out there.

I maximised this to give me as much height as I could manage on my printer.

It includes mounting points for acrylic sides (~445mm wide x 520mm tall).

I am currently awaiting delivery of some twinwall 4mm polycarbanate for the back and sides and regular acrylic for the front. The twin wall is fairly cheap and should provide excellent insulation.Hopefully it should bounce the light round inside a bit too. For anyone in the UK I am using plasticsheets.com as a fairly cheap supplier. Many companies seem to charge a lot for delivery which bumps up the price a lot. Slightly dissapointed that the twinwall came with a blue canvas tape binding the open edges. This tape is practically impossible to remove. Its not hugely noticeable when fitted but I may get some white tape to cover it up so it matches the table legs. The 4mm wirks well for the sides, but going with 6mm would be better if you have the choice. The 4mm acrylic is also a little too thin, but still works nicely.

The mounting brackets are designed so 6mm (I am using 4mm) sides fit flush with the edge of the table. The leg 'stilts' have a screw mounting hole in the central shaft so they dont fall off the when lifted.

Door Hinges - Pick either left or right hand mounting. Pesonally I printed 2 left hand countersunk hinges to screw to the table legs and 2 left hand pan head hinges along with the back plate to bolt to an acrylic front panel. The hinges are base on a remix of airald's design. I have added a designspark mech CAD model here if you need to modify any dimensions. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1933479.

The door handle is designed to print on its side with a back plate that minimises stresses on the acrylic door.

The original stilt raises the table by 120mm(print is 170mm tall) I have also uploaded a shorter 80mm stilt as well as a taller 140mm stilt in case your needs vary. You will need to subtract 40mm or add 20mm when sizing the side panels and doors in this case.The Designspark Mechanical(free) CAD model is included too if you need to make other alterations.

21/01/2017 - Added a locating spigot that can be screwed to the base Lack table to help keep all the legs in line. Before assembly use on of the Stilts to measure the correct location of the spigot. Drill a pilot hole and use a shot countersunk self tapping wood screw to attach.

Printer:

Wanhoa Duplicator i3

Rafts:

No

Yes

0.3mm

15%

Notes:

3 shells
6 top and bottom layers

Each stilt takes about 7hours to print depending on settings.

title: Arduino Offset Header Jig
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
If you've ever made a custom Arduino shield using standard perfboard, you know the two digital IO headers are separated by a non-standard distance and won't line up with your perfboard.

I tried using needle nose pliers to bend the pins to match and failed miserably, so I created this thing. It's a pair of jigs for bending an 8 pin header the precise amount needed to mate any perfboard with your Arduino.

Use the first jig to bend all 8 pins at an angle, then use the second jig to straighten the ends. Voila!

In the original version, the first jig worked perfectly as the bending force is primarily against the header body, but the second jig needed improvement because the tiny bit of material between pins would break when attempting the bend. This is solved in the latest release which uses metal inserts made from... a set of header pins.

To make the second jig, gently tap an 8 pin header into the 8 holes as shown in the last picture and clip off the excess with flush cutters.

description.text:
Broke the original 'read-light' key chain holder on this garage door opener from Sears. As I no longer shop at Sears and found the 'replacement' cost of new opener obnoxiously expensive I developed my own.

It's basic, but it works and I generate a new housing for the electronics in under an hour. The tolerances are tight and tried this on a couple of different materials successfully.

Updated with my free cad files. Not sure why this was suddenly so popular (for my stuff anyway) I'm sure someone else can do a better job and can work from my humble beginnings.

Notes:

Recommend Ninaflex for the button. PETG for the top where the keychain will be attached.

This sculpture was inspired by an image of a flying Great White Shark that is native to Seal island in South Africa.
It is the only place on earth where one can witnessing a one ton shark flying out of the water. A now you can capture this moment of raw power and agility of this majestic killing machine by printing this sculpture for your desktop.
See the great white burst out of your table top, or perhaps use it as a wall sculpture. follow us on http://www.facebook.com/xyzworkshop

This desktop sculpture is printed in two parts, the Shark and the Water splash, both with supports turned on and glued together. Two versions are featured in this thing.
The Green version printed by myminifactory themselves at .25mm layer. The colored version printed by us is not painted but uses two different colored filaments grey filament for the shark and blue for the water.

description.text:
Case for GM328A component tester. which is yet another a variant based on the rather wonderful universal transistor and component tester developed by Markus Frejek, and later Karl-Heinz Kübbeler. A full description of the project is available here:

http://mikrocontroller.net/articles/AVR_Transistortester

This case fits the variant with graphical display and one test button sold by Banggood and probably elsewhere called GM328A. The case includes a compartment for the battery. The pinout for the 14 pin ZIF test socket is printed on the case, for reference. Note that there are very many different variants of this tester in the market.

You need four M3x16 (or thereabouts) countersunk screws for assembling the top and bottom sections. It works best if you thread first using an M3 tap.

The inner structure of the press button is critical to get the right height. You may have to clean it up a bit to get the right fit, or possible add thin shims. There is a parameter call 'knob_fudge' that can be used for fine tuning, if you so wish.

Please examine the pictures of the PCB carefully to make sure you have the right PCB before you start your print. Cases for other variants of more or less the same basic design are available here http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:797733 and here http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:694790 http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1580922

description.text:
This is a modified version of sprylo's Roller Blind Bracket.

I increased the width of the channel for the round end of a roller blind to make this a complete set.

NOTE: You will have to mirror one of the files in your slicer to make a set, depending on your application.

I've included sprylo's original files for a simpler download experience, all credit goes to him.

Dies ist ein einem Amulett ähnliches Gehäuse für eine kleine elektronische Schaltung. Das Amulett ist in der Lage jede beliebige Farbe anzuzeigen, abhängig von seiner Lage oder der gerade darauf einwirkenden Beschleunigung. Trägt man es am Körper, so wird es in Abhängigkeit von der Bewegung des Trägers verschiedene Farben zeigen bzw. flackern. Gedacht ist es als Accessoire für selbstbewusste Menschen mit einem Hang zum Auffallen auf Parties oder ähnlichen Veranstaltungen. Vielleicht können sich aber auch nur Nerds dafür begeistern.

Es basiert auf einem Beschleunigungssensor vom Typ MMA8451, einem Adafruit Trinket und einem Neopixel Ring mit 12 LED's, sowie einem 250 mAh Lipo Akku.

Leider bleibt nach dem Laden der Bibliothek für den MMA8451 kaum noch Platz für eigenen Programmcode im Trinket. Selbst für einen Laufeffekt am Anfang sind nicht mehr genug Bytes übrig. Für aufwendigere Programme, wie zum Beispiel ein Bremslicht, sollte man darum auf einen Pro Trinket zurückgreifen. Dann passt aber leider das Gehäuse nicht mehr. :-)

author: rsr02

description.text:
I'm planning some new features ETA ~autumn '17

  • Modified housing (include dart chamber part into main body)
  • Dart sensors (IR) (more precise movement, currently hardcoded in software)
  • Additional pre-trigger button to spin up the wheels before fire (or keep spinning)
  • Body version for other motor size(s) (e.g 1106)

progress update 16 Dec. 2016
hereby I'll publish my firmware, I'm not a professional programmer so go easy on it ;)
https://github.com/willumpie82/DUFDL

progress update 15 Dec. 2016

  • Moved from ESP8266 to Teensy3.2 (cortex M4),
  • Progress on firmware is good, everything finally works (on teensy), code need some polishing.
  • I'll create a Git-hub for all the source files soon
  • 208-GT2 belt still underway, current 200-GT2 is to short.
  • I will release the accesoiry top mount soon

Inspired by the works of JesseKovarovics FDL-1 & FDL-2, I designed my own dart launcher. It is will probably receive some small modifications and the firmware is far from finised, currently writing the firmware for an ESP8266, but waiting for an i2C IO extender (ESP is short on IO)
it can run on an Arduino but because of the PWM signals, the Ardiuno runs short on clock ticks (16Mhz)

shopping list:
https://github.com/willumpie82/DUFDL/blob/master/BOM.xlsx

Controlling Setting (Controls via 3 buttons, Menu, Plus & Minus)

  • launch mode (Single, Double, Triple, Full Auto)
  • launch speed (0-100%)

  • clip size (countdown)

  • this design is work in progress, most parts already works.
    soon i will make the sourcecode & design files available (Solidworks)

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2

Notes:

most body parts printed in PLA (10-30% infill), flywheels in ABS with high infill for better balance

Although the designs are made with 3D printers in mind but somehow i cant get the orientation in Thingiverse correct (it might sound trivial) place al parts with the flat most side facing down.
Support
The body, grip, rear side panels and barrel connector require support. Best to print the clip holder without support, the internal cavity (for locks etc) are small enough to bridge. any support here is impossible to remove (resolvable support will work)

title: terminator style lower arm prosthetic
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
t800 style lower arm prosthetic.

The lower part is hollow, so it can be fitted on to the prosthetic arm socket.
Scale the arm to the right size, also do the same to the finger parts.
Then the t800 lower socket can be heated , so the socket will be moldable. The push the t800 lower part onto the prosthetic arm socket.

The prosthetic socket is NOT included in this model.

Printer Brand:

Deltaprintr

Printer:

Deltaprintr Kit

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Notes:

I printed this in PETG, and used a 0.6 nozzle. With 0.4 layer highed

The middle section of the arm gives a non manifold, but this gives no problem during slicing (slic3r).

fitting the t800 style arm to the prosthetic socket

The lower part of the t800 style arm is hollow. Just heat this part so it's moldable. Then place this on to the prosthetic socket. Make sure the alignment of the arm is right.
After cooling down you can connect these parts using glue or a mechanical fixture.
I added some coil springs to make sure the fingers will extend after flexion.
The lower and the mid part are bolted together. Put a rubber spacer between the parts, so it can rotate. Make sure the bolt is glued properly. I made one with mid part on top of the lower part and sliced this file. So i can be printed in one go. However if you do this. you can't let the arm make pro- or supination.

I added filaflex on the fingers. Now the fingers can flex, by pulling the filaflex. I will redraw the finger tips so bolts are not needed to fixate the filaflex

comments.text: Quit breaking your printer! :)  What's the issue? And I love the way the carbon fiber prints come out. The layers kind of melt together at smaller layer heights, and have a smoother overall appearance. The only downside is the abrasive qualities of it.  It WILL eventually widen a brass nozzle.  I went through a 1kg spool and noticed it towards the end.  Another 1kg and the nozzle was zorched.  If you dont mind constantly adjusting the nozzle diameter in you slicing program its not that bad...but the last .5kg was a rough ride (I constantly had issues). title: Newmar Hood Release Block
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
When I try to release the front (hood?) compartment latch...I pull on the release handle. When I go to open the compartment...the latch has re-engaged. I needed my wife to continuously pull on the release handle while I lift the hood and place it on it's support rod.

So, to enable me to open the front compartment, without assistance... I have created this block...which will stay attached to the release mechanism with a lanyard. When I want to open the compartment...I'll pull the release handle...place the block over the shaft to hold it in the release position...while I go and lift and prop the front compartment door (hood?)

550 cord lanyard

I melted the end of 550 cord and pulled it thru a napkin to make a pointed end. I fed the pointed end of the 550 cord thru the eyelet in the Hood Release Block. After having the end threaded thru the eyelet...I remelted the end and let it become flared and rounded...so it will not pass back thru the eyelet. The other end of the cord is tied around the shaft of the Hood Release Cable... I did this to prevent it from getting lost. It will always hang right where I need to use it. The fit is pretty tight along the hexagonal shaped shaft...which is kinda good...so it will stay in place when I need it.

Version 2 was created to make the fit a little looser... Easy on/off without friction. It still sit's atop the hexagonal shaft very securely.

comments.text: Quite a challenge for the 101Hero. After doing the hex star from101hero.com, I'd advise a test cube or something simple as a first print. Print speed is critical for this light-weight little printer; even though the creator gives 14 mm/s as default, that speed can result in layer shifting on some 101Hero machines. For mine, I found 12 mm/s to be maximum with 10 mm/s giving better results. You just have to be prepared to wait. My 101Hero did a decent Benchy in just under four hours - far from perfect but acceptable for the price of the printer. The Cute Octobowl (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1739912) will take over nine hours.

title: Gameboy Advance SPi - Raspberry Pi inside a Gameboy

description.text:
Here's a fully working Raspberry Pi inside a Gameboy Advance SP.
Short video of it from all angles: https://youtu.be/VBCmUc5d7g4

There's more than a few of these projects that put Pis in Gameboys, but I've only seen a couple that used the Advance SP and they both cut all kinds of holes in the case.

I didn’t want to cut any new holes and it had to close up completely; no wires sticking out, no extra buttons in places they’re not meant to be. It had to look as much like a normal Gameboy as possible.
This build doesn’t have any sound.
The backlight button was programmed to be a “lights out” button on mine, and shuts down the Pi so I can turn it off easily.
This isn’t a complete guide, but it should show you enough to figure out how I did this and that.
This was not an easy build.

Parts list:
• Gameboy Advance SP aftermarket case
• Gameboy Advance SP hinges
• Raspberry Pi Zero
• Micro SD card
• Adafruit perma-proto half-sized https://www.adafruit.com/products/1609
• Adafruit Powerboost 500 https://www.adafruit.com/products/1944
• 1000mAh Battery (Dimensions: 5 cm x 3.4 cm x 0.6 cm) http://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/171247223018
• Adafruit PiTFT - 320x240 2.8" TFT+Touchscreen for Raspberry Pi https://www.adafruit.com/products/1601
• GPIO Ribbon Cable (any wire will do but this was thin and flexible) https://www.adafruit.com/products/1988
• Power switch
• 4x4x0.8 SMD tactile push buttons http://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/111726375227
• 4x4x1.5 SMD tactile push buttons http://www.ebay.co.uk/itm/111726375227
• Optional: Gameboy cartridge

Guides are attached
Ask me about anything I forgot to mention, I'm happy to answer

I also wanted to put two type A usb ports out the back, both sticking out a bit from the console. I want to keep the slider volume and power switch in the locations that they are in. I also want to tackle putting sound in, hopefully using the gba sp speaker along with making a hole below where the volume slider is for an aux port. I'm still very much in the beginning planning stages of this process and am still sizing up my parts.I was thinking if i had some room left over in the screen section of the case i could store a board or two up there. I want this to be able to close up normally with most things inside with the exception of the two usbs in the back. What are your general thoughts on this. If possible could you give input on each decision so i can get a more accurate sense of what is possible.
comments.author: Fireblast950

comments.text:
• Buttons above the AB buttons: These would be pretty simple to add, the software I used actually already has these programmed and ready, I just didn't want to drill extra holes in the case. It might be best to use some tactile buttons that poke through slightly, rather than trying to fit extra bits of plastic into that space.
  • Analog stick below dpad: Adding this would mean that the screen wouldn't close properly since it needs to be pretty flat. N64 games don't run very well on the Pi Zero anyway, so I wouldn't get your hopes up.
  • Extra USB ports: there's plenty of room for this so with a bit of resizing of the holes, that should be fine. You might consider micro USB ports instead to keep it all inside the case, but you'd obviously need to use an on-the-go adapter for full-size USB. You can still access the Pi's micro USB from the front of the case by removing the game cart, so using a hub with that would mean you don't need to add any extra.
  • Sound: I didn't expect to be able to fit this in when I made mine so you'll have to look at options for this yourself. There are oblong shaped speakers that might be slimmer, i'm not sure.
  • Board behind the screen, I wouldn't expect to fit more than one board up there, if you made your own one, you'd be able to have it run the screen and audio?
  • Closing up: adding an analog would be a problem. The extra buttons would need to be pretty much flush with the plastic. I wouldn't add the plastic lens thing for the screen as it makes it thicker, but it does look nicer with it. Fitting stuff inside was a challenge, you could sacrifice battery life and use a smaller battery if necessary.

comments.text:
Ampersands,
Is there a way to make this using the ports currently on the Gameboy, rather than sacrificing the cartridge slot?
comments.author: Carlover416

comments.text:
I'm not sure what you mean by sacrificing the cartridge slot? You want to be able to put a real game in there?
I haven't cut any new holes in the case as I made use of the original ports, the charge lead connects through the original power switch hole and the power switch is where the volume slider used to be.
Placing the Pi where the cartridge goes meant that it could still be accessed easily. If you wanted to make room for some sort of game cart reader, you'd need to use a much smaller battery so that the Pi can be moved further in. My build already has an empty half centimeter gap at the back where the original charge sockets would go, you could use that? I thought about adding extra micro USB sockets there.
The battery I used is almost the exact size as the original and it fits where the original would go, but there's no reason you need to do the same if you had a mod in mind.

description.text:
This design is a vacuum turbine, that is able to generate enough force as to attach it to the ceil. It works with a small motor (the motor of the tail rotor of small RC electric helicopter).
It is a preliminar study, so, the design is parametriced in order to allow the modification of the motor, the stator or the turbine.

I've been grateful surprised by the first results. The idea is to use the rotation speed instead of torque using not only the centrifugal force also the Ventury effect.

I've used a bearing of 10 mm (outer diameter) 3 mm(inner) and a ring width of 4 mm. The screws are all M3.

author: DestinyStlGenerator

description.text:
This is a full set of the roads, settlements and cities that comprise the game tokens in the Settlers of Catan board game. Yes, there are other options out there, but the problem is, that if you want to print a whole set, then doing so in one go usually amounts to one of the pieces dislodging from the print bed and ruining the whole lot.

In these files, I have made their edges touch so that the extruder tip doesn't have to stop/start which increases the risk of losing that first foundation of each part.

Once the print is done, the pieces come apart very easily at their corners and don't leave much of an edge at all.

If you found this useful, please share your work and be sure to peruse my other submissions which are almost as varied as they are many:

remixed_from.author: ScribbleJ
remixed_from.title: Automatic Platform Leveling and Z Calibration made SUPER EASY

description.text: Use this thing to set the Z-Minimum height on a Thing-O-Matic automagically!

This thing has allowed me to dramatically improve the Z-Resolution of my prints. I no longer have squashed first layers (skirts) and the Z height is much closer to ideal. This build has a lot of setup, but once set works remarkably well! This is based on ScribbleJ's auto platform leveling http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:7008. This thing does not automatically level the platform, but does automatically set the Z height. If for some reason your probe or electric connectors fail, this can drive the print head forcefully into your build platform. Use with care! Before you begin, it is a good idea to do the following:
  • Make sure your thermocouple is well insulated to prevent running accidentally running current through it.
  • Ground your extruder head via a wire from the heater support to the PSU body. This will protect your extruder board from a failed heater core dumping +12V through the thermocouple, or if you short your probe to the extruder head.
  • Heat your HBP to around 100C and make sure your HBP is truly level.
    • Parts needed:
  • 4xM3 nuts and bolts
  • 2mm bicycle spoke
  • stranded wire (about 2 meters)
  • 4 wire connector (CD Audio cable) similar to the connectors on the endstops
  • 0.4mm brass or aluminum plate (a beer can would work)
  • 10K ohm resistor
  • heat shrink tubing
  • 3x aligator clips
    • Part 1 - Install and test probe:
  • Print both parts (this is set up for a right hand mount) - the larger part holds the probe; the smaller part makes the electrical connection.
  • Replace the spacer on the right side of the extruder plate with the probe holder.
  • Cut the bike spoke to ~80mm and file one end to a rounded point.
  • Load the spoke into the holder with the point down. Push the spoke down at least 10mm lower than the print head for now and loosely secure it using the M3 nuts and bolts.
  • Attach a ground wire to pin 3 of the connector (black wire in the image).
  • Attach a second wire (+5V) to pin 4 of the connector. Attach this to the Z min connector on the motherboard (red wire in the image).
  • For mounting the probe to the right side of the extruder, thread the +5V wire through the back right hole in the acrylic base. Thread the ground wire through the back left hole.
  • Attach the ground wire to the HBP (I used a solderless lug and attached it via one of the leveling screws)
  • Use aligator clips to temporarily attach the the 10K ohm resistor to the +5V wire and the probe for testing.
  • Scrape a small amount of tape from the HBP and lower the probe so it touches the HBP surface. I used a spot at the center of the right edge, on the Y axis of the HBP.
  • Open ReplicatorG control panel and set the "Jog Mode" to .1mm and attempt to lower the Z axis. If the probe is functioning properly, the Z axis should not lower. Try moving the Z axis up and down checking that the Z axis stops when the probe touches the HBP.
  • After you are satisfied with the functioning of the probe, solder the resistor onto the metal plate. Trim and load the small metal plate into the holder (see the image). This will make the electrical connection between the +5V wire and the probe. Note the larger grove to the right center. This is just the right size for a 1/4watt resistor.
  • Solder the +5V wire to the resistor (don't forget the heat shrink tube!)
  • Thread the holder onto the probe and tighten down.
    • Part 2 - Calibrate probe and set offsets:
  • Scrape any plastic from the print head to make sure it can be lowered all the way to the plate.
  • Heat the HBP to 100C to ensure that it is in the same stat as when you build.
  • Align the probe with the bare spot on the HBP.
  • Loosen the probe and lower the head by hand until it just touches the HBP.
  • Push the probe down gently so it is firmly in contact with the HBP and tighten the bolts. The goal is to have the probe at the same height as the extruder head. If it is higher, the head will be driven into the HBP. If it is lower, it will drag through your prints!
  • Open replicatorg and paste in the following code and run it. Replicator will complain that you are trying to home in the wrong direction. This is normal and expected. You should proceed and follow the instructions. BE READY TO HIT STOP OR TURN OFF THE MACHINE IN THE EVENT YOUR PROBE FAILS! (*** Txoof-O-Matic calibration script ***) (*** Based on Thing-O-Matic Calibration***) (*** Script ***) (*** Created 15 March 2012 ***) (*** ***) (*** This script will guide you through ***) (*** calibrating the start position ***) (*** on your Thing-O-Matic. ***) M18 (This disables the stepper motors.) M01 (Please align the probe with the test area. Once aligned, the HBP will warm upto 110C.) M109 S110 (Set the HBP to 110C) M6 T0 (Wait for the HBP to reach temperature) M01 (Please keep a hand on the stop button or the power supply! If the probe fails, the head will continue to drive into the HBP possibly causing damage. Be ready to stop it!) G161 Z100 (Home to probe area) M18 X Y(Disable motors) M01 (Carefully align the print head to the true center of the HBP) G92 X0 Y0 Z0 A0 B0 (Declare the current position to be (0,0,0,0,0)) G162 Z F500 (Home Z axis maximum; go until reaching the end stop.) G161 X Y F2500 (Home X and Y axis minimum; go until reaching the end stop.) M131 X Y Z A B (record the current coordinates to the motherboard) M18 (disable motors) M00 (Congratulations, your coordinates are now saved! To tweak them, use the 'Motherboard Onboard Preferences' dialog in the Machine menu.
    Note: You will need to re-generate your gcode files using a new profile in order to use these saved settings.)

    You may want to save this calibration code to use again later if anything changes to reset your offsets.

    • Part 3 - Configure replicatorg to use calibrate Z offset for every print:
    NB! The start code is for a TOM with HBP and stepstruder. It can easily be modified to work with any other TOM. Simply use only the "homing" sections.
  • Run the gcode below to determine the proper settings for your Start code: M01 (This will center your HBP and allow you to determine the coordinates of your probe area.) G161 X Y M132 X Y G90 G1 X0 Y0 F2500 M18 Z M01(Lower your Z axis to the center of the platform then open the control panel. Jog the X and Y axis to center your probe in your test area.)
  • Open the control panel and jog the HBP until your probe is over the test area. Record the X and Y values.
  • Open the Start+HBP+Stepstruder.gcode and edit the following lines to match your X and Y values: G1 X28 Y0 F1000 (move the HBP to the probe position)
  • Save the code and test by running it as a build in replicatorg. Keep a hand on the stop button or the power switch incase something fails!
  • Once you are satisfied that this gcode works for your printer, either make a symlink from the machines/thingomatic/ directory to your version, or pop your version into the machines/thingomatic directory. I replaced the start+HBP+Stepstruder.gcode with my auto-homing version to match my TOM w/ HBP. Note that you will need to update this EVERY time you upgrade replicator.
  • Make a test print! Keep your hand on the power switch the first few times until you are satisfied that the homing works properly!
    NB! ReplicatorG will complain about homing in the wrong direction each time it starts. This is normal. Don't panic!

I couldn't quite figure out if you could move the switch up and down.  Also, how do you keep the flag on the switch from dragging through your prints?

comments.text: No, mine isn't adjustable. I designed it to be about 1mm higher than the nozzle to keep it from dragging. I adjust the first layer thickness by changing the Z-homing as usual.
comments.author: txoof

comments.text: Just a thought, still working on it (just did this at work). Use a watch band clip that has the spring built into it. This give you about a .1" give just in case. Need to find a way to mount and make a holder.
comments.author: jamesarm97

comments.text: Just a comment, So one of the best known ways to destroy an extruder board is pass current back up the grounded thermocouple. Make 100 percent sure your thermocouple is insulated from the aluminum head and nozzle. While unlikely, if the head jams into the HBP and somehow the nozzle short to any power source, this eliminates you from destroying the extruder controller. It's happened often enough to warrant this message. This design is good in that the hbp plate is grounded but again, you never know. I cannot stress enought the thin layer of tape is all that protects the extruder controller from certain destruction.
comments.author: Unknown

comments.text: The parent version of this thing runs +5V directly through the extruder head.  I didn't think this was a good idea, so I made the probe completely separate.  The HBP is grounded and the extruder head is also grounded via  a wire that runs to a lug on the PSU body.  If by some chance the probe should come in contact with the extruder head, or my heater core fails along with the kapton insulation on my thermocouple, the ground wire should protect everything.

title: Mini LED Spotlight With Barn Doors

description.text:
Here is a very cheap, very shapeable solution for accent and miniature lighting. This LED flashlight (around $4) has a focusable beam. The mounts are based on Mole Richardson classic movie light design with a modern twist.
The barn doors print in one piece. Carefully wiggle to loosen each joint. The doors nest into a tight little package in this order: right, left, bottom, top, as shown in the animated gif:
http://digidavedvd.com/Public/Misc/Barn%20Doors.gif
They can snug fit onto the light directly or you can use the backer if you want to use gels to color or soften the beam. A swatch pack of gel filters (you can find these at Expendables outlets, usually for free) is the perfect size to insert color and/or diffusion. Attach the backer with 3mm filament rivets. There is a lever at the top of the doors designed to retain gels.
The spotlight tilt has a printed-in tensionable hinge designed to work with the included knob or any 1/4-20 knob or bolt.
There is also a snoot and cookie that pressure fits onto the doors for creating interesting light breakup. I will design more patterns - follow me to stay updated.
I found these lights here, but they are fairly easy to find elsewhere:
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01CB2ZTYQ/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o00_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

Designed to work with this lightstand:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1907813
Use a 1/2" long 1/4-20 set screw or threaded rod.

This is part 4 of my thing-a-day campaign. Follow me for updates and fun new stuff. So far this week I've shared these other designs:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1913561
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1918270

author: supinemonkey

title: Ceiling lamp - round spacer - post mounting mount variation with puzzle piece deconstruction for one handed assembly ML

description.text: Our ceiling lamp in the living room requires more space for cables than is provided by the existing power outlet hole. That means I could not push the cone shaped cover all the way up so a bit of space was left empty. I now filled that gap with this THING. As I have only one hand I cannot just mount all kinds of insanely difficult stuff so I made this a two puzzle piece slide in support thing.

title: Wearable Arc reactor for  Electroluminescent Tshirt

description.text:
This is a 3D printable overlay for my Arc reactor Tshirt. You can buy these tshirts off ebay, or thinkgeek etc, but they kinda look lame if you are not standing in the dark (or if they are switched off- as you will see in the photo).
The EL panel lights up and flashes etc, so this looks great, but not a lot like the movie prop. I have gotten it as close as I can with available dimensions of the EL panel, and have tried to keep it thin enough to still be wearable.
Print, Paint, Add copper wire (in my case I used thin copper sheet from an EMF screen from a ciruit board). Please share your makes :)

5/1/17 - Added module for CP2102 USB to serial adapter and dual USB connector extension. The USB socket is connected - #1 to Raspberry Pi free USB port and #2 to CP2102 which will be connected via USB cable to my EFIS RS232. All connection were soldered. The antenna is direct plug to RTL Nano. Holes for antennas are shape different with matching cable end for easy identification.

1/15/17 - Added some modules for newer Nano 2+ which is little bit longer.

12/25/16 - Added some more modules for different adapters and positions, side mount for holding 2 mini antennas (you need to print updated top with side holes) front or back (reversed) load, added full face GPS plug with thin wall recess for easy cable cutout.

This is a somehow modified Slim Case by helno - SD card opening is cut deeper for easy removal, more vent holes. The modules can be design to fit a different components mounted to Raspberry Pi - GPS, AHRS etc.

Hardware is 2-56 screws and brass inserts for plastic -
https://www.mcmaster.com/#99362A100,
https://www.mcmaster.com/#90241A087

comments.text: I think I understand this project. I use a Pi with two SDRs and an external GPS on a cable (so it can be away from RF noise of the SDRs).  I think I want a base, a top module, the side mount to store antennas), and the stretched module with GPS (plus a plug) so I can route the cable out.  What's the difference between the GPS plug and the "full" GPS plug?
comments.author: matthewgast

comments.text: The "GPS plug" is printed with cutout for the cable, the "full GPS plug" has full face (in case you're not using the external GPS) with a recessed back face for easy cutout in case you'll want to route the GPS antenna out of the case. It means GPS plug - slot for cable made already, Full GPS plug - you will have to cut the slot with knife.
comments.author: matthewgast

comments.text: Do you have a side mount for the high Gain antennas?

I have some speaker stands that just seemed a little too maleable. When I cranked down the speaker mount friction lock to the aluminum tube of the stand, it bent. :-\ So I designed these inserts to reinforce the tube at the point where my speaker stands put the most pressure on the tube.  Ha, take that, physics!

Check the inside diameter of your speaker stand. Mine measured around 33mm, give or take a bit. The outside measured something like 34.5mm.  At one point I had a very slight taper in the design to allow for bends or indentations when inserting this thing into the tube.  I went through several iterations, so I can't remember if this one has that feature.  You could of course modify my file to adjust that if you want.  I added a lip at the top to prevent the insert from escaping further into the tube than I intended. So far so good.

title: MISR Clips for Boscoyo Strips
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
Here is a set of clips to fit the Boscoyo pixel strips.

The metal ones James sells are approximately the shape and size as the MSIRSingle in this collection.

The single and dual ones are designed to have the strip fold over and back on itself. The others are not.

I wanted some additional shapes for butt splicing so I created a varieity of clips in case others needed slight variations.

The two bungie clips (ones with wings) are designed to take 5mm bungie cords with the plastic balls on them. The cords are available at Ace as well as ebay and other online sources. The reason I made these is to spread the bungie out to help prevent the strips from twisting. The traditional method is to poke the bungie through the large 12mm hole. This creates a single point axis for twisting. By moving the bungie out to the edges of the strips it should help to reduce twisting. You can, of course use wireties on the wings instead of bungie. Your call.

I recommend you print these with 4 top/bottom/perimeter layers at .3mm layer thickness and out of ABS that has UV stabilizers (MakerGeeks says theirs does).

title: Wanhao D6 Right Side Spool Mount - Remix
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a remix of a remix.
Aero3D originally remixed the MakerBot Replicator side spool holder designed by SORE THUMB (the_mighty_sparrow) to fit the Wanhao Duplicator 6. It's a great design but to fit my work area, I needed it to work on the right-hand side of the printer. Also, because I have side panels fitted, I needed it to be a bit more stable.

It's a simple remix. I've widened the mount points and create a block on the outside 'leg' that sits just above the side panels. For extra rigidity, I have also removed the stub axles and created a mount point for a full axle. Two axle sizes are included, based on the hub sizes on the filament spools currently on my shelf. The 'fat' one is for spools with holes of at least 50mm and the 'thin' axle for spools with a max of 32mm.

I've tried to align the STLs so they fit on the print bed but you may have to move and/or rotate.

UPDATE
I had a few issues with some (badly rolled) filaments springing over the side of spools during rapid movements so I have added a filament guide around the same mounting system and sized to fit between the two side arms. You may need to pack the outside with a piece of foam (or similar) to lighten the fit against the side of the printer.

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator 6

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

Medium

Infill:

15%

Notes:

No supports on the brackets. You probably need supports for the fat axle but if you have dual cooling and are printing PLA, the thin axle should print without supports. I used 20% infill for the brackets and 15% for the axles.

description.text:
The Roberval balance is a weighing scale with two horizontal beams one above the other connected to two vertical beams supporting the weights to be compared.

Because the beams form a parallelogram, no matter where the weight is placed in the plates the balance works properly, compared to a simple beam scale which is sensitive to where the weights are placed in the plate. See it in action at https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bg7IBTMdyf0

Use this tool to compare the weight of any two small objects! It shows differences as small as 1 gram.

See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roberval_balance for more historical and scientific information about the Roberval balance.

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

Original Prusa i3 MK2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

10%

Notes:

Print the base, top bar, bottom bar, riser, 2 plate holders, 2 plates and 2 plate sleeves. The full model is not meant for printing, just to show the assembly.

Print all parts plat.

Assembly

Using super glue, glue the plate holder to the bottom of the plate. Pay attention to the orientation of the plate holder: the end the farthest from the holes goes into the plate. Make sure the plate holder is square with the plate. Slip the plate sleeve on the plate holder and glue it to the bottom of the place.

Using M3 screws attach the plate holders to the top and bottom bars and the bars to the riser. I had some partially threaded screws (meaning the lower half of the screws have threads and the upper half is smooth) so I used that but regular screws work too.

Glue the riser into the base.

M3 10mm partially threaded screw

Designed in Autodesk Fusion 360.

See and modify the original model at http://a360.co/2fFNAwu
CCSS

Kindergarden: Describe and compare weight. Which object is lighter and heavier. Grade 1: Measure weight indirectly. Order 3 objects by weight. Grade 2: Measure weight in standard units. Add standard weights to find the weight of an object. Grade 3: Solve problems involving weight measurement.
Lesson plan adapted from the Common Core Measurement & Data page

Describe and compare measurable attributes Directly compare two objects with a measurable attribute in common, to see which object has "more of"/"less of" the attribute, and describe the difference. For example, directly compare the heights of two children and describe one child as taller/shorter.

Measure weights indirectly Order three objects by weight; compare the weight of two objects indirectly by using a third object. Express the weight of an object as a whole number of weight units, by putting multiple copies of a lighter object (the weight unit) on one balance plate; understand that the weight measurement of an object is the number of same-weight units that balance the scale. Limit to contexts where the object being weighted is balanced by a whole number of weight units with no gaps or overlaps.

Measure and estimate weights in standard units. Measure the weight of an object by adding numbered standard weights to balance the scale. Measure to determine how much heavier one object is than another by adding numbered standard weights to balance the scale, expressing the weight difference in terms of a standard weight unit.

Solve problems involving measurement and estimation. Measure and estimate masses of objects using standard units of grams (g), kilograms (kg), and liters (l).1 Add, subtract, multiply, or divide to solve one-step word problems involving masses that are given in the same units by using the balance to represent the problem.
Scale, objects to measure, units weights of 1 g, 5 g, 10 g, etc.

description.text:
This simple box can hold an Apple TV (4th gen.) and can be fixed with one M6 screw into a single VESA-mount hole on the back of a Flat-TV.

I used a short M6 screw: The screw head should not be thicker than 3mm and a maximum diameter of 13mm (screw dimensions: M6, 13x13mm). The screw-length however, depends on the TV's VESA hole (sorry, I don't know, how deep you can screw).

Printer:

bq Hephestos 2

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Yes

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

50% or more

Notes:

I used Brim (20 lines) and had supports for the rounded corners on the bottom of the box and inside of the screw hole.

Set the infill to 50% least. If you set the wall thickness to 1.3mm, you will need an infill the back-pad only (see the "How I Designed This" section). The infill part will be a minimum and give more rigidity to the upper section of the pad, where the screw whole is.
I used 20% infill and 1.2mm thick walls. It works, but you may not tighten the screw to much.

Designed using FreeCAD

I designed the box using FreeCAD and then exported the final object as STL.

First I sketched and extruded two boxes (one into the other): one is an "edged" version of half an Apple TV, the other is the same box, but with the dimensions of the outer-frame (that is the 1st box plus 2.5mm wall thickness on 3 sides - left, right, bottom). Then I cut out the inner box out of the outer box.
In the next step I sketched/pocketed the front and bottom spaces and added the additional pad on the back > all just rectangles for the moment.

The pad on the back ensures a small distance from the flat TV and also takes a part of the screw-head pocket. In that pad I pocketed the screw hole (6mm through all) and the screw head (13mm, 3mm deep starting from the inside wall of the box).

Finally I added some 1mm fillets on most of the edges on the front and the top of the box, and most importantly the wider fillets for the rounded corners of the Apple TV (on the bottom of the box) and for the front rectangle (rounded edges on the top front of the box).

description.text:
Your party is carving its way through the massive horde of Roper and take notice that several of the roper have turned their gaze, in horror, to something entering the opposite end of the cavern. Many of these roper have fallen silent, as they desperately attempt to blend in with the cavern, using their stony camouflage. Your wizard has noticed what the roper are so terrified of and quickly cast a veil of invisibility and implores the rest of the party to fall silent, in an attempt to bypass this new horror. The ancient orb floats into the view of the rest of the party, snarling and glaring as each of its eye stalks dart in every direction. Slowly, this ancient aberration turns its glare and all of its eye stalks to stare directly into the invisible abyss and with a deafening, demonic shriek, several of the eye stalks glow and flash. The wizard, and several roper, noticed that the veil had been dispelled and prepare for the imminent assault of this ancient beholder. The barbarian, who wasn't going to wait for the beholder to act first, is already lunging, battleaxe in hand, at the floating mass of eyes.

Roll for initiative.

Thanks everyone who have taken an interest in my models and tokens. This is my second beholder I have created and uploaded. I will continue to make more tokens as long as you enjoy printing and using them.

description.text:
playground_spool

Alarm system for your 3D printer spool, to let you know of finished or failed prints, based on Adafruit's Circuit Playgroud

  • Github repo: https://github.com/fede2cr/playground_spool
  • Thingiverse: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1920690

Description

The project is composed of two parts:

  • A 3D printed adapter to attatch a Circuit Playground plus a battery, to a 3D printer fillament spool.
  • Software for the Playground to monitor the rotation of the spool by using the accelerometer. Once the rotation stops, either the printer finished the job properly, or something like a clog in the extruder made a print fail.

Parts

  • playground_spool_v1.stl: First prototype, it fits fine one some brands of spool, but not all
  • playground_spool_v2.stl: Second try. Bigger fillet in the bottom, 150mAph lipo battery pocket, reinforcement for the playground bumper. This version is recommended.
  • playground_spool_v3.stl: 3rd. Fillers in the battery slot for better fit, the playground bumper went up because I couldn't get it in with the previous version, and also the reinforcent went a bit down.

Instructions

  1. Print this parts with support using a semi-flexible fillament, with the playground bumper facing up.
  2. Load the software into the Circuit Playground
  3. Put the Playground inside its bumper in the 3d printed piece, connect the battery and tuck in it's pocket
  4. Put the 3d printed part inside the fillament spool and start a new print
  5. Once either the print finishes, or there is an extruder malfunction, the Playground will detect loss of rotation (LOR) and beep to get your attention

TODO

  • The battery can be tighter in the pocket
  • The pocket for the spool holder could be smaller for less material

Wishlist

  • To average the rotation speed, and then indicate visually if it's rotating faster or slower than the average. Eye candy.
